  "text": "TcdA has been described as an enterotoxin because it causes exudative colitis. TcdB is cytotoxic and causes epithelial cell collapse, apoptosis, and cell death. TcdA and TcdB are both large molecular weight toxins (308 and 209 kDa, respectively) belonging to the large clostridial toxin family [CITATION_1] . Some strains of C. difficile, particularly those associated with livestock, produce binary toxin, the function of which remains speculative even though it has been associated with so-called ''hypervirulence'' (Kuehne et al., 2014) . It is thought to enhance microtubule protrusion from gut epithelial cells, leading to formation of a network of mesh around the bacterial cells resulting in adhesion [CITATION_2] .",
